references: We consider four learning tasks, summarized in TableÂ 1.

We consider four tasks motivated by
real-world applications of federated learning.
The tasks are summarized in TableÂ 1 of the main paper and the distribution of data across the clients is visualized in FigureÂ 6.

From TableÂ 10, we see that partial personalization can result in a 34%percent3434\% to 42%percent4242\% reduction in the memory consumption across the models and datasets considered in the experiments.
We compare FedAlt and FedSim for speech recognition in TableÂ 11. We find that input layer personalization with FedAlt has the smallest word error rate of all the models considered.

We see from TableÂ 12 that the effect of the final finetuning is much smaller than the improvements from personalization.
For instance, the improvements from finetuning are close to 00 for FedAlt on the StackOverflow dataset. For GLDv2, the finetuning accounts for <0.5absent0.5<0.5pp of improvement, whereas personalization overall accounts for 555 to 151515pp.

TableÂ 12 also shows that the final finetuning helps FedSim more than FedAlt. However, FedAlt still outperforms FedSim, as we saw in TableÂ 4.
Overall, this shows that FedAlt is a better algorithm than FedSim. The final finetuning helps FedSim make up some percentage points in accuracy, but not enough to make up its gap with FedAlt.

We see from TableÂ 13 that all algorithms perform similarly for the stateless setting. Nevertheless, we see that FedAlt obtains mild improvements over both FedSim and finetuning for GLDv2, e.g., 0.240.240.24pp with adapters.

We see from TableÂ 14 that the final finetuning accounts for most of improvements in the stateless case. For instance, for GLDv2, the final finetuning accounts for 11.6811.6811.68 and 10.4210.4210.42pp out of a total of 12.6712.6712.67 and 11.7611.7611.76pp for FedAlt and FedSim respectively. However, the personalized federated training (stepÂ (b) of the pipeline; cf. Â§B.2) still leads to an increase in accuracy of 111 to 1.341.341.34pp.

FedSim in turn yields a higher accuracy than simply finetuning the personal part of the model by a margin of 0.120.120.12pp for StackOverflow/Output Layer and 2.552.552.55pp for GLDv2/Adapter.

Furthermore, we observe that the difference between FedAlt and FedSim is much larger than the standard
deviation across runs. For instance, under output layer personalization for GLDv2, this difference is 0.40.40.4pp (=8Ã—=8\times std).

TableÂ 12 also shows that the final finetuning helps FedSim more than FedAlt. However, FedAlt still outperforms FedSim, as we saw in TableÂ 4.
Overall, this shows that FedAlt is a better algorithm than FedSim. The final finetuning helps FedSim make up some percentage points in accuracy, but not enough to make up its gap with FedAlt.
